       "   'content': '## Evidence\\n\\n- Lucy states: \"We are both insane.\"\\n- Minna responds to Craig: \"Of course not!\"\\n- The puzzle establishes that:\\n  - Vampires always lie; humans always tell the truth.\\n  - Half the inhabitants are insane: insane individuals believe true statements to be false and false statements to be true.\\n  - The other half are sane: sane individuals believe true statements to be true and false statements to be false.\\n- Therefore:\\n  - Sane humans and insane vampires make only true statements.\\n  - Insane humans and sane vampires make only false statements.\\n- The sisters are one human and one vampire, with no known sanity status.\\n- The statements from Lucy and Minna contradict each other, meaning one is telling the truth and one is lying.\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\nInspector Craig deduced that **Lucy is the vampire**.\\n\\nThe reasoning is as follows:\\n- Since Lucy and Minna contradict each other, one is telling the truth and one is lying.\\n- Given that one is a human (truth-teller) and one is a vampire (liar), and considering the sanity rules, the only consistent scenario is that Lucy is the vampire.\\n- If Lucy were sane, she would tell the truth, so her statement \"We are both insane\" would be true. But that would mean both are insane, which contradicts the requirement that only one is a vampire.\\n- If Lucy were insane, she would believe her statement to be true, but since she is insane, she would actually be lying. Thus, \"We are both insane\" is false, meaning at least one is not insane. This aligns with the fact that Minna says \"Of course not!\" — a lie if Lucy is insane, which fits the pattern.\\n- If Lucy were the human (truth-teller), then \"We are both insane\" would be true, implying both are insane. But then Minna, as a human, would be insane — a contradiction, since humans are not insane in this setup.\\n- Therefore, Lucy must be the vampire, and Minna is the human.',\n",
