       "  {'role': 'tool',\n",
       "   'name': 'fetch_url',\n",
       "   'content': '## Evidence\\n\\n- Lucy states: \"We are both insane.\"\\n- Minna responds: \"Of course not!\" (i.e., \"We are not both insane.\")\\n- The puzzle involves two sisters: one is a vampire, one is a human.\\n- Vampires always lie; humans always tell the truth.\\n- Half the inhabitants are insane: insane individuals believe true statements as false and false statements as true; the other half are sane and correctly evaluate truth.\\n- The statements from Lucy and Minna contradict each other (one claims both are insane, the other denies it), so they cannot both be telling the truth or both lying.\\n- After evaluating all possible combinations of vampire/human and sane/insane, only two scenarios remain consistent:\\n  - **Case 3**: Lucy is a sane vampire (thus lying), Minna is a sane human (thus telling the truth). Lucy’s statement \"We are both insane\" is false, and Minna’s statement \"We are not both insane\" is true.\\n  - **Case 4**: Lucy is an insane vampire (thus telling the truth), Minna is an insane human (thus lying). Lucy’s statement \"We are both insane\" is true, and Minna’s statement \"We are not both insane\" is false.\\n- In both valid cases, Lucy is the vampire.\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\nLucy is the vampire. This conclusion is reached by analyzing the logical consistency of the sisters\\' statements under the rules of truth-telling and lying, accounting for both sanity and vampirism. Despite differing sanity states in the two valid scenarios, Lucy is consistently the vampire in both. Therefore, Inspector Craig can determine that Lucy is the vampire.',\n",
